Anonymous Tue 28 May 2019 09:06:45 No.23394035 Report
Quoted By: >>23394641
>pic related, from previous thread.

Something missed is that animals are measured from nose-tip to base of tail (in the science world, not trophy hunter dick-measuring contests). You have to remember that conversion to bipedal adds the length of the legs more or less. So, a "medium" wolf of 90 cm body length would be something like 120 or 130 cm tall standing up. Anyone who owns a medium to large-ish dog can tell you that when they plant their front feet on your chest they can look you in the eye. Easily.

A "large" wolf could stand on its hind legs and easily be 150 cm, or even 170 cm, depending on more exact measurements and other factors. For instance, a bipedal evolved anthro wolf would likely develop a different leg length compared to it's four-footed ancestors. It's not unreasonable at all to imagine an anthro wolf reaching normal human heights, even up to 2 meters. But, certainly, 180-185 cm (6 feet) would not be unusual and could even be the norm depending on other evolutionary factors.

Similarly with weight, wolves would likely be lighter in build than typical humans, but not crazy light. A 185 cm wolf might weigh on around 70 kg (~155 lbs.), which is a bit 'scrawny' by some measures, but not crazy so. At 75 kg they would be very close to a normal 6 foot man at just under 170 lbs.

So, some species might be smaller, but the larger end of the known species in our real world would be within statistical size limits of humans. Small evolutionary adaptations could easily make them nearly identical or a bit larger. It was just 10,000 to 120,000 years ago that Dire Wolves roamed North America, and those fuckers were at least the size of the largest wolves that are alive today.

As would be saber-toothed cat waifurs. And those don't even require the fossil record. Tigers, lions and jaguars already give us an idea of what an 8 foot 220 lb. anthro waifur a bit more directly evolved from our Stone Age would look like.

>"Neanderanthro"
At a much earlier stage in evolution on the way to full anthro erectus status. I can see some fascinating possibilities in a universe where a modern human from our world steps into a world sort of the equivalent of what ours was 100,000 years ago with many anthro species competing on an evolutionary scale in a race to full upright/bipedal body form. But, the majority of them still tend to "walk" on one knuckle about half the time, and can lope along sort of on all fours at need.

Rather than discussing just size justification/evolution, one of the things I think furry artists neglect the most is the vast potential for different body proportions and postures. Almost everything is human proportion & posture with very minor cosmetic variation. Monsters (such as werewolves) & xenos are where you start to get much more variation, especially in body posture. Very rarely does anyone ever try to design by how evolution shaped a species, like figuring out how to structure the skeleton and then build musculature.
